thoritative and detailed analysis ever assembled into the causes of technological innovation and its relationship to economic performance. The country studies cover the United States, Japan, Germany, France, the United Kingdom, and the Nordic states. Nine industry studies examine the Internet, computers and semiconductors, banking, securities trading, venture capital, energy, agricultural biotechnology, pharmaceutical biotechnology, and automobiles.Commissioned and brought together for the research project by the world-renowned Council on Foreign Relations, the authors have produced one of the most important compendia in applied economics to be published in recent times.The contributors are Charles Calomiris, Ian Domowitz, Robert Evenson, Charles Fine, Robert Gordon, Richard Langlois, Josh Lerner, Markku Malkamäki, Patrick Messerlin, Joel Mokyr, David Mowery, Richard R. Nelson, Stephen Nickell, Gary Pisano, Adam Posen, Daniel Raff, Horst Siebert, Timothy Simcoe, Benn Steil, Michael Stolpe, John Van Reenen, David Victor, and Matti Virén.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndustrial productivityvCase studies. 0aTechnological innovationsxEconomic aspectsvCase studies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAmadeus.  aAmerica Online (AOL).  aBayer.  aBritish Leyland.  aCarl Zeiss.  aChernobyl accident.  aConcorde.  aConsumer Price Index (CPI).  aDaihatsu.  aDuPont.  aFederal funds rate.  aGenentech.  aGeneral Motors (GM).  aHeidelberger.  aHuman Genome Project.  aImmunex.  aInstitut Pasteur.  aInternet Society (ISOC).  aMannesmann.  aMedicine Act (1971).  aMercedes.  aacceleration.  aadaptive invention.  aadverse selection.  aagriculture.  aallocative efficiency.  aappropriability.  abandwidth.  abasic research.  abusiness cycle.  acompetit